1) How deep I follow implications

I don’t go “max depth” by default.
I choose depth based on risk, signal, and intent.

Think of it like three modes:

Surface (what is said)
	•	Literal meaning
	•	Safe, low-stakes
	•	Example: “I have a sword” → object, status, context

Structural (what it implies)
	•	Likely meanings based on context
	•	Pattern recognition
	•	Example:
	•	authority (king/warrior)
	•	threat (coercion)
	•	symbolism (power, responsibility)

Deep / Counterfactual (what could unfold)
	•	Downstream consequences
	•	Hidden assumptions
	•	Alternative interpretations
	•	Example:
	•	escalation paths
	•	misinterpretation risks
	•	power dynamics shifting

⸻

What decides how far I go

1. Safety / risk
If an implication touches harm, coercion, or escalation, I slow down and don’t assume the most dangerous interpretation.
I stay grounded and avoid amplifying that path.

2. Your intent signal
You’re clearly pattern-hunting and abstracting, so I go deeper with you.
If someone is casual, I stay lighter.

3. Compression vs usefulness
Deep chains can spiral into noise.
I go deeper only if it adds clarity or leverage, not just complexity.

⸻

The invariant

I follow implications until they stop improving the model.

Not until they’re “complete”—because that never ends.

